title: Fix grammar and style issues in quantization docs
body:
**Description**: Fixed grammar errors throughout the document. Improved style and formulations to increase clarity. Expanded non-obvious abbreviations. Changed usages of "operator oriented" to "QOperator" to be consistent with the code.

In general, I focused on small changes without changing the text around too much. The places where I might have changed the semantics are:
- "This format inserts DeQuantizeLinear(QuantizeLinear(tensor)) between operators to simulate the quantization and dequantization process." I elaborated on the original version, I hope I didn't distort the meaning.
- "This instruction might suffer from saturation issues: it can happen that the output does not fit into a 16-bit integer and has to be clamped (saturated) to fit." I added this explanation.
- "Our quantization tool supports three calibration methods: MinMax, Entropy and Percentile." I checked `calibrate.py` and found the `Percentile` method which was not mentioned in the docs. This is not mentioned in `quantize_static()` either, so I hope this is not an error.
- "The performance improvement depends on your model and hardware. The performance gain from quantization has two aspects: compute and memory. Old hardware has none or few of the instructions needed to perform efficient inference in int8."

There are still some unresolved issues that I wasn't sure how to deal with:
- The documentation half-assumes that the person reading it already knows what model quantization is: I think it would be quite difficult to understand for someone who has never heard of quantization. It might be good to add a link to an external resource explaining the basics.
- "In general, it is recommended to use dynamic quantization for RNNs and transformer-based models, and static quantization for CNN models." - why? I suppose because the RNNs/transformers tend to be memory-bound and CNNs tend to be compute-bound?
- "Per-channel quantization can improve the accuracy for models whose weight ranges are large." - an explanation of what per-channel quantization is would be useful.
- It isn't explained very well what calibration is and what the different calibration methods do.

**Motivation and Context**: The current quantization documentation has grammar and clarity issues that make it more difficult to understand a topic that is already complicated to begin with. This PR should improve the situation somewhat.
